onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Alauda</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
Roman measure; <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('about 4736 km',WIDTH,156)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>about 3106 English miles, taking the Roman foot (296 mm) as 0·97 English.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
For this and similar sums see Index, <I>s.v.</I> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sestertius</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
When ordinarily they would be put to death.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
That is, in correcting the bill after it had been passed and filed, as explained in the following sentence.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
When the senate passed a decree that Caesar should disband his army before a given date, the tribunes Mark Antony and Quintus Cassius exercised their privilege and vetoed it
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Civil_Wars/1A*.html#2.6
	"TARGET="Caesar_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Caesar, <I>B. C.</I> 1.2.6‑7)</A>; not only did the senate disregard the veto, but the tribunes were obliged to see safety in flight
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Civil_Wars/1A*.html#5
	"TARGET="Caesar_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>id.</I> 1.5.1‑2)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Officiis/3B*.html#R21
	"TARGET="Cicero_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
3.82</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
<I>Phoenissae</I>, 542 f.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
Way.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
Knights (as well as senators) had the privilege of wearing a gold ring, and must possess an estate of 400,000 sesterces.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Per tumultum</SPAN> is a strong expression for <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">contra legem</SPAN> or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">extra ordinem</SPAN>, since the Lex Sempronia provided that the consuls be appointed to their provinces before election; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#19.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">xix.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">prandium</SPAN> was the first substantial meal of the day, taken about noon; the translation "dinner" is used advisedly.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
In token of his restoration to the rank of knight, which he forfeited by appearing on the stage; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#33.1.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xxxiii</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
The first fourteen rows above the orchestra, reserved for the knights by the law of L. Roscius Otho, tribune of the commons, 67 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Euripus</SPAN>, the strait between Euboea and Boeotia, was used also as a common noun, meaning "a ditch" or "canal."

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: Caesar's <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">euripus</SPAN> in the circus was a safety measure. Typically, Nero had it removed. For further details and sources, see
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Circus.html#euripus
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,SmithSub1,WIDTH,SmithSubWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
this passage
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
The year had previously consisted of 355 days, and the deficiency of about eleven days was made up by inserting an intercalary month of <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-two</SPAN> or <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-three</SPAN> days after February.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources on Caesar's calendrical reform, the old intercalary month, etc., see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Calendarium.html#Caesars_reform
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,SmithSub1,WIDTH,SmithSubWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Calendarium</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
Plebeians, connected in some way with the treasury.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: As vague as this is, it is by no means certain. For a careful discussion, see
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Aes_Equestre.html#tribuni_aerarii
		"TARGET="princeps"
