onMouseOut="nd();">
this passage
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>, and the further links there.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
<I>i.e.</I>, of the commons, with reference to the distribution of grain.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
The derivation of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">parricida</SPAN> is uncertain, but it cannot come from <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pater</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">caedo</SPAN>. In early times it meant wilful murder of a freeman; XII. Tab. <SPAN CLASS="small italic">ap.</SPAN> Fest. <I>s.v.</I>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">si qui hominem liberum dolo sciens morti duit, paricidas esto</SPAN>; later, it was associated by popular etymology with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pater</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">caedo</SPAN>, and used also in the modern sense of the word.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
Epilepsy, called <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">morbus comitialis</SPAN>, because an attack was regarded as sufficient cause for the postponement of elections, or other public business. Sometimes a seizure was feigned for political reasons.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Latus clavus</SPAN>, the broad purple stripe, is also applied to a tunic with the broad stripe. All senators had the right to


<A ID="p63x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p63)</SPAN>wear this; the peculiarity in Caesar's case consisted in the long fringed sleeves.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
While a girdle was commonly worn with the ordinary tunic, it was not usual to wear one with the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">latus clavus</SPAN>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/Institutio_Oratoria/11C*.html#3.138
	"TARGET="Quintilian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Quint.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XI</SPAN>.3.138</A>. The looseness of the girdle was an additional peculiarity.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
The word play on <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tertia</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pars</SPAN>) and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Tertia</SPAN>, daughter of Servilia, as well as on the two senses of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">deducta</SPAN>, is quite untranslatable. The first meaning is given in the translation, and the second is implied in the following sentence. <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Macrobius/Saturnalia/2*.html#2.5
	"TARGET="Macrobius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Macrobius, <I>Saturnalia</I>, 2.2.5</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
M. Actorius Naso; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#9.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. ix.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
The words <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">liberorum quaerendorum causa</SPAN> are a legal formula indicating that the purpose of marriage is to beget legal heirs.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
Caesar was in reality <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">propraetor</SPAN>, but <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">proconsul</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pro consule</SPAN>) is sometimes used of the governor of a province, regardless of his rank.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
Apparently about half the usual price: see Index <I>s.v.</I> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sestertius</SPAN>.


