"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/caesar/gall8.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>De Bell. Gall.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>, preface, 5‑6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
That is, Caesar reduced his reports to book form. If the book was a <I>roll</I>, the writing was arranged in columns, parallel with the edges (or long sides) of the roll. If it was a <I>codex</I>, several sheets were folded and fastened together and the writing was arranged on each page in one or two columns. His predecessors merely took a sheet, or sheets, and wrote from side to side and from top to bottom, without columns or margins.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
Through Gaius Volusenus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Gallic_War/4*.html#21
	"TARGET="Caesar_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Caes. <I>B. G.</I> 4.21.1)</A>. Suetonius's words <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">per se</SPAN> do not necessarily imply that Caesar went to Britain himself for this purpose.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A>
The significance of this name can only be conjectured. Salutio was an actor of mimes, mentioned by Pliny, <I>N. H.</I> <A HREF="
