http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/horace/serm1.shtml#7
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Horace, <I>Serm.</I> 1.7, etc.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
The college of fifteen priests (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quindecimviri sacris faciundis</SPAN>) in charge of the Sybilline<!-- sic --> books.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Bonum factum</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sit</SPAN>) was a formula prefixed to edicts, here used in jest; <I>cf.</I> the similar formulas in proposals to the senate,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#58.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Aug.</I> lviii.2</A>,<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The Loeb edition has '+BadF+'lviii.3'+CloseF+'',WIDTH,100)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Caligula*.html#15.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Calig.</I> xv.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#note43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on xlv.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pons suffragiorum</SPAN>, a temporary bridge of planks over which the voters passed one by one, to cast their ballots;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/att1.shtml#14
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Cicero\'s Epistulae ad Atticum to that letter'+Lat2+LatSearch+'pontes</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cic. <I>Ad Att.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.14</A>;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.fasti5.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('Click here for<BR>Book 5 of Ovid\'s Fasti'+Lat2+LatSearch+'http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.fasti5.shtml</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Ovid, <I>Fasti</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.634</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A>
Properly said of a temple; according to
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Florus/Epitome/2E*.html#2.91
	"TARGET="Florus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Florus, 4.2.91</A>; one of the honours bestowed on Caesar was <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fastigium in domo</SPAN>; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Caesar*.html#63.9.2
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Plutarch, <I>Caesar</I>, lxiii</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A>
Possibly "from behind," though it is hard to see how a wound <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">paulo infra iugulum</SPAN> could have been dealt from that position. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Aversum</SPAN> has better mss. authority than <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">adversum</SPAN>, is <I>a priori</I> more probable, and is supported by Plutarch's version; but it may mean "turned away."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
A pointed instrument of bone or metal, for writing on waxen tablets.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources, plus an engraving, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Stilus.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Stilus</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
To inherit a share of his estate in the event of the death of the heirs in the first degree or their refusal to accept the inheritance; it was often a mere compliment.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
<I>Cf.</I> the apparition at the Rubicon;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xxxii</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
Caesar was beloved by the Jews, not only because he had overthrown Pompey, who had violated their Holy of Holies, but because of many acts of kindness besides.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
<I>Cyropedeia</I>, 8.7.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
About an hour before sunset.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:loss_of_his_priesthood" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:loss_of_his_priesthood
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">flamen dialis</SPAN> had to be married, could not divorce, and if his wife died had to resign: thus by putting away his wife, Caesar was automatically bombing himself out of the priesthood. See the article
		<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Flamen.html#flaminica
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,SmithSub1,WIDTH,SmithSubWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Flamen
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I> for these and many other details.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:plain_called_Stellas" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:plain_called_Stellas
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
Usually referred to as "the district of Stellae", a relatively remote area of eastern Campania on the borders of Samnite territory, over which one of the Samnite wars was fought, as recorded by Livy
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/livy/liv.9.shtml#44
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,190)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">IX</SPAN>.44)</A>. The area can hardly be characterized as a plain.<!-- uuu: add Google Map -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:grain_and_oil_ration" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:grain_and_oil_ration
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
At roughly 8.75 liters, the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">modius</SPAN> is a close equivalent to the English peck (9.09 litres); the Roman pound, however, was about 325 grams, much less than the English pound (just under 457 grams). At any rate, Caesar's distribution was around 90 liters of grain and 3 liters of oil: enough of one to cook the other in, and a basic ration for one person for 3 months.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:tesselated_and_mosaic_floors" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:tesselated_and_mosaic_floors
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d</A>
A translation error in the Loeb edition, made more striking by the fact that "tessellated floors" (the usual spelling, by the way) <I>are</I> mosaic floors. The Latin <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tessellata et sectilia pavimenta</SPAN> refers to:

<TABLE CLASS="basicH white image">
	<TR>
		<TD><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="279" HEIGHT="186" SRC="
Images/Gazetteer/Periods/Roman/Topics/Architecture/Elements/decorative/pavements/mosaic/alias.jpg
		" ALT="
[image ALT: A detail of a Roman mosaic floor, showing a lobster.]
		"></TD>
		<TD ROWSPAN="2" VALIGN="middle"><DIV CLASS="contents">
and
		</DIV></TD>
		<TD><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="279" HEIGHT="186" SRC="
Images/Gazetteer/Periods/Roman/Topics/Architecture/Elements/decorative/pavements/opus_sectile/alias.jpg
		" ALT="
[image ALT: A detail of a Roman floor with a geometric design; it is an example of opus sectile.]
		"></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR>
		<TD><DIV CLASS="contents">
			<P CLASS="center">
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tessellata pavimenta</SPAN>:
			<P CLASS="justify">
floors made of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tesserae</SPAN> (small cubes, most often black and white, sometimes colored) arranged in patterns — <I>i.e.</I>,
<I><!--
			<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Periods/Roman/Topics/Architecture/Elements/decorative/pavements/mosaic/home.html
			"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
-->
mosaics<!--</A>--></I>;
			<P CLASS="right">
Bevagna:
			<BR>
Roman Baths, v. di Porta Guelfa
		</P></DIV></TD>
		<TD><DIV CLASS="contents">
			<P CLASS="center">
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sectilia pavimenta</SPAN>:
			<P CLASS="justify">
floors made of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">crustae</SPAN> (sliced veneers of precious marbles) cut in specific shapes to form what our translator should have called
			<I><A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Periods/Roman/Topics/Architecture/Elements/decorative/pavements/opus_sectile.html
			"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
opus sectile</A>.</I>
			<P CLASS="right">
Ostia Antica:
			<BR>
House of Amor and Psyche
		</P></DIV></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR>
		<TD COLSPAN="3"><DIV CLASS="caption-centered">
The photos are at roughly the same scale.
		</DIV></TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:an_Aegisthus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:an_Aegisthus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">e</A>
An appalling thing to say of someone, and one wonders whether Pompey had any inside information. In the kinky and bloodthirsty legends of the Greeks, Aegisthus was the son of Thyestes sleeping with his own daughter: so that his mother was his <SPAN CLASS="whole">half-sister</SPAN>, and his father was his grandfather. Abandoned as a baby, he was adopted by his uncle Atreus who had killed Thyestes' children and fed them to him as stew. Understandably, Aegisthus, the original angry young man, winds up killing his uncle then cuckolding his uncle's son Agamemnon as soon as the latter goes off to war.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 justify">
Caesar did indeed cuckold a lot of people, including Pompey, who in tagging him as Aegisthus, was giving himself out as Agamemnon doing his warrior's duty overseas while this shiftless lecher was stealing his wife: but Pompey was also getting back at Caesar in a classic and very hostile piece of psychoanalysis.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:elegant_and_transparent" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:elegant_and_transparent
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">f</A>
At least, such is the general meaning of the passage, which is peculiarly difficult to translate. For the details, see Prof. Rolfe's own
		<A HREF="
E/Journals/TAPA/45/Notes_on_Suetonius*.html#5
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Notes on Suetonius (TAPA 45:46‑47)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Hall_of_Pompey" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:Hall_of_Pompey
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">g</A>
More usually referred to today as the Curia of Pompey. For details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Curia_Pompei.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,200)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curia Pompei
		</A>
in Platner and Ashby's <I>Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome</I>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:my_child" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#ref:my_child
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">h</A>
It is quite possible to speculate that Caesar was being literal, and that Brutus was his son. For one piece of evidence see above,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#50.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
50.2</A>.



